m This, and the greater part of the seholastie memorial verses, are found for the first time in the Summum Loyicales of Petrus Hispanus, afterwards Pope John XXI. who died in 1277. He does not, however, profess to be the author of them; indeed some, including the present, are also noticed by his contemporary Aquinas, as established mnemonies. In slight measure he has been anticipated by the Greeks. A mnemonic for the opposition of modals is found in the synopsis attributed to Psellus, and one for the syllogistio moods in Nicephorus BlemmidaS. But the genuineness of that portion of the works of Aquinas has been questioned, and the treatise which goes under the name of Psellus is probably a transla- tion of the Summulae of Hispanus. The latter work is thus our earliest undoubted authority for these curious specimens of scholastie ingenuity. See below, p. 84. note z.
